INTRODUCTION TO LINUX
Q1. What is an Operating System?
An OS is system software that acts as a bridge between hardware and applications — it manages CPU, memory, storage, I/O devices, files, and processes while providing an execution environment for programs.
Key Functions:
Process management
Memory management
File system management
Device (I/O) management
Security and user management
Resource allocation
Examples: Linux, Windows, macOS, Android
Mnemonic: "PM-FIRD" — Process, Memory, File system, I/O, Resource allocation, Device/user security
Q2. Difference between Linux, UNIX and macOS
LINUX
Free, open-source, Unix-like OS built on the Linux kernel.
Open-source and free
Multiuser + multitasking
Secure and stable
Portable and highly customizable
UNIX
Original multiuser, multitasking OS — proprietary, foundation for Linux/macOS. Used in enterprise/mission-critical systems.
Multiuser + multitasking
High stability and reliability
Strong security
Portable across specific supported hardware only (Linux is more portable than UNIX)
macOS
Proprietary, Unix-based OS by Apple.
Unix-based
Proprietary (developed by Apple)
Uses the XNU hybrid kernel
Secure and stable
Optimized for Apple hardware only
(Correction note: Linux is "Unix-like" — not built on original UNIX source code — while macOS is technically "Unix-based," since it's certified compliant with the Single UNIX Specification. Ye difference exams mein pucha ja sakta hai.)
Q3. What is VirtualBox?
A Type-2 (hosted) hypervisor by Oracle that lets multiple guest OSes run on top of a host OS using hardware virtualization.
Key Features
Supports multiple guest OSes (Windows, Linux; macOS only on Apple hardware — licensing restriction)
Uses hardware virtualization (Intel VT-x / AMD-V)
Provides virtual CPU, RAM, storage, network devices
Supports snapshots and virtual disk management
Cross-platform host support (Windows, Linux, macOS)
Q4. What is VMware?
A virtualization software (hypervisor) developed by VMware Inc. that runs multiple OSes on a single physical machine.
Key Features
Type-2 hypervisor in desktop editions (e.g., VMware Workstation, Fusion) — VMware also has Type-1 hypervisors (e.g., ESXi) for enterprise use
Uses hardware virtualization (Intel VT-x / AMD-V)
Allows creating VMs with separate CPU, RAM, disk, network
Supports snapshots, cloning, and resource allocation per VM
